          is   providing   new  insights  on  the  particle  acceleration
          processes  long  known  to  be at work in the magnetospheres of
          isolated  neutron  stars.  According  to a standard theoretical
          interpretation,  in neutron stars' magnetospheres particles are
          accelerated  along  the  B  field lines and, depending on their
          charge, they can either move outward, to propagate in space, or
          be  funnelled  back,  towards the star surface. While particles
          impinging  on  the  neutron star surface should heat it at well
          defined spots, outgoing ones could radiate extended features in
          the  neutron star surroundings. By detecting hot spots, seen to
          come  in  and  out  of  sight  as  the star rotates, as well as
          extended  features  trailing  neutron stars as they move in the
          interstellar  medium,  XMM-Newton provides the first end-to-end
          test to the particle acceleration process.


  
