          fraction  of  {\em Swift} Gamma-ray Burst (GRB) afterglows tens
          to  hundreds  of  seconds  after  the  trigger  of  the  prompt
          $\gamma-$ray   emission   phase.   These   flares  are  usually
          attributed  to the late time activity of the central engine. We
          suggest  a  new central engine model to account for these X-ray
          flares.  In  this  model,  the GRB central engine is a rotating
          magnetized  supramassive neutron star (SMNS). When the SMNS has
          lost  its significant part of angular momentum, it collapses to
          a  black  hole  and  produces a Poynting-flux dominated outflow
