          Title:  Saturation  Physics  in  Ultra High Energy Cosmic Rays:
          Heavy Quark Production
          Authors: V.P. Goncalves, M.V.T. Machado
          Comments: 4 pages, 3 figures
          In  this  work  we  estimate  the heavy quark production in the
          interaction of ultra high energy cosmic rays in the atmosphere,
          considering  that  the  primary  cosmic  ray  is  a proton or a
          photon.  At  these  energies  the saturation momentum Q_{sat}^2
          stays  above  the  hard  scale  \mu_c^2=4m_c^2,  implying charm
          production  probing  the  saturation  regime. In particular, we
          show  that  the  ep  HERA  data  presents a scaling on \tau_c =
          (Q^2+\mu_c^2)/Q_{sat}^2.  We derive our results considering the
          dipole  picture and the Color Glass Condensate formalism, which
          one  shows to be able to describe the heavy quark production in
          photon-proton and proton-proton collisions. Nuclear effects are
          considered  in  computation of cross sections for scattering on
          air  nuclei.  Implications on the flux of prompt leptons at the
          earth are analyzed and a large suppression is predicted.


   
