          Title: Limits on Neutron Lorentz Violation from Pulsar Timing
          Authors: B. Altschul
          Comments: 9 pages
          Pulsars  are  the most accurate naturally occurring clocks, and
          data  about  them  can  be used to set bounds on neutron-sector
          Lorentz  violations.  If  SO(3) rotation symmetry is completely
          broken  for  neutrons,  then pulsars' rotation speeds will vary
          periodically.   Pulsar   timing   data   limits   the  relevant
          Lorentz-violating coefficients to be smaller than 1.7 x 10^(-8)
          at at least 90% confidence.


   
