          Title:  Ellipsoidal  Variability  and Long Secondary Periods in
          MACHO Red Giant Stars
          Authors: A. Derekas, L. L. Kiss, T. R. Bedding, H. Kjeldsen, P.
          Lah, Gy. M. Szabo
          Comments:  4  pages, 4 figures, accepted for publication in ApJ
          Letters
          We  present  a period-luminosity-amplitude analysis of 5899 red
          giant  and  binary  stars  in the Large Magellanic Cloud, using
          publicly  available observations of the MACHO project. For each
          star,  we  determined new periods, which were double-checked in
          order    to    exclude   aliases   and   false   periods.   The
          period-luminosity   relations   confirm   the  existence  of  a
          short-period, small-amplitude P-L sequence at periods shortward
          of  Seq.  A.  We point out that the widely accepted sequence of
          eclipsing binaries between Seqs. C and D, known as Seq. E, does
          not  exist.  The  correct  position  for Seq. E is at periods a
          factor  of  two  greater,  and  the  few  stars genuinely lying
          between  Seq.  C  and  D  are  under-luminous  Mira  variables,
          presumably  enshrouded  in  dust. The true Seq. E overlaps with
          the  sequence  of Long Secondary Periods (Seq. D) and their P-L
          relation  is  well  described  by a simple model assuming Roche
          geometry.  The  amplitudes  of  LSPs  have  properties that are
          different   from   both  the  pulsations  and  the  ellipsoidal
          variations,  but  they  are more similar to the former than the
          latter,  arguing  for  pulsation  rather  than  binarity as the
          origin of the LSP phenomenon.


   
astro-ph/0608621 [abs, ps, pdf, other] :
