          Comments: 21 pages, 11 figures, published in Phys.Rev.D
          Journal-ref: Phys.Rev. D74 (2006) 044030
          We present long-term (~10^4 M) axisymmetric simulations of
          differentially rotating, magnetized neutron stars in the
          slow-rotation, weak magnetic field limit using a perturbative
          metric evolution technique. Although this approach yields
          results comparable to those obtained via nonperturbative (BSSN)
          evolution techniques, simulations performed with the
          perturbative metric solver require about 1/4 the computational
          resources at a given resolution. This computational efficiency
          enables us to observe and analyze the effects of magnetic
          braking and the magnetorotational instability (MRI) at very
          high resolution. Our simulations demonstrate that (1) MRI is
          not observed unless the fastest-growing mode wavelength is
          resolved by more than about 10 gridpoints; (2) as resolution is
          improved, the MRI growth rate converges, but due to the
          small-scale turbulent nature of MRI, the maximum growth
          amplitude increases, but does not exhibit convergence, even at
          the highest resolution; and (3) independent of resolution,
          magnetic braking drives the star toward uniform rotation as
          energy is sapped from differential rotation by winding magnetic
          fields.


   
