          the binary pulsar PSR J1713+0747
          Authors: O. G. Benvenuto, R. D. Rohrmann, M. A. De Vito
          Comments: 11 pages, 9 figures. Published in MNRAS
          Journal-ref: 2006 MNRAS 366, 1520B
          Splaver and coworkers have measured the masses of the white
          dwarf and the neutron star components of the PSR J1713+0747
          binary system pair by Shapiro Delay. We attempt to find the
          original configuration of this system performing a set of
          binary evolution calculations to simultaneously account for the
          masses of both stars and the orbital period. We considered
          initial masses of 1.5 and 1.4 \msun for the normal (donor) and
          the neutron star, respectively. We assumed two metallicity
          values (Z = 0.010 and 0.020), and an initial orbital period
          near 3 days. We assume that the neutron star is only able to
          retain \lesssim 0.10 of the matter transferred by the donor
          star.
          Calculations were performed employing our binary hydro code
          that handles the mass transfer rate in a fully implicit way
          together with state-of-the-art physical ingredients, diffusion
          and a non-grey atmospheres.
