          collapsar disks may lead to fragmentation near the radius where
          helium photodisintegrates, because of the strong cooling
          provided by this process. This physics sets clear physical
          scales for the fragmentation conditions and the properties of
          gravitationally bound clumps. Collapse of a fragment proceeds
          until the neutrons become degenerate; a neutron star of mass
          ~0.1-1Msun may result. We find that tidal disruption of a
          fragment and accretion by the central black hole are too rapid
          to account for the durations of observed X-ray flares from long
