          (Abridged) Chandra and Hubble ACS observations of 11 early-type
          galaxies probe the low-mass X-ray binary (LMXB) - globular
          cluster (GC) connection. We explore the optical properties of
          270 GCs with LMXBs and 6,488 GCs without LMXBs. More massive,
          redder, and more compact GCs are more likely to contain LMXBs.
          Unlike Galactic GCs, a large number of GCs with LMXBs have
          half-mass relaxation times > 2.5 Gyr. We fit the dependence of
          the expected number of LMXBs per GC, \lambda_t, on the GC mass
          M, color (g-z), and half-mass radius r_{h,cor}, and find that
          \lambda_t \propto M^{1.24\pm0.08} 10^{0.9^{+0.2}_{-0.1} (g-z)}
          r_{h,cor}^{-2.2^{+0.3}_{-0.4}}. Our fit rules out that the
          number of LMXBs per GC is linearly proportional to GC mass and
          that most GCs with high X-ray luminosities contain a single
          LMXB. The detailed dependence of \lambda_t on GC properties
          appears essentially equivalent to a dependence on the encounter
          rate \Gamma_h and the metallicity Z, \lambda_t \propto
