          July 4-7, 2006
          Gamma-ray astrophysics depends in many ways on multiwavelength
          studies. The Gamma-ray Large Area Space Telescope (GLAST) Large
          Area Telescope (LAT) Collaboration has started multiwavelength
          planning well before the scheduled 2007 launch of the
          observatory. Some of the high-priority multiwavelength needs
          include: (1) availability of contemporaneous radio and X-ray
          timing of pulsars; (2) expansion of blazar catalogs, including
          redshift measurements; (3) improved observations of molecular
