          We combine Spitzer and ground-based observations to measure the
          microlens parallax of OGLE-2005-SMC-001, the first space-based
          such determination since Refsdal proposed the idea in 1966. The
          parallax measurement yields a projected velocity \tilde v ~ 230
          km/s, the typical value expected for halo lenses, but an order
          of magnitude smaller than would be expected for lenses lying in
          the Small Magellanic Cloud itself. The lens is a weak (i.e.,
          non-caustic-crossing) binary, which complicates the analysis
          considerably but ultimately contributes additional constraints.
