          Title: Binary star progenitors of long gamma-ray bursts
          Authors: M. Cantiello, S.-C. Yoon, N. Langer, M. Livio
          Comments: Accepted for publication in A&A Letters
          We present a binary channel for the progenitors of long
          gamma-ray bursts. We test the idea of producing rapidly
          rotating Wolf-Rayet stars in massive close binaries through
          mass accretion and consecutive quasi-chemically homogeneous
          evolution. The binary channel presented here may provide a
          means for massive stars to obtain the required high rotation
          rates. Moreover, it suggests that a possibly large fraction of
          long gamma-ray bursts occurs in runaway stars. This can have
          important observational consequences for both the positions of
          GRBs, and their afterglow properties.



