          Title: Searching for primordial black hole dark matter with
          pulsar timing arrays
          Authors: Naoki Seto, Asantha Cooray
          Comments: 4 pages, 2 figures, Accepted for publication in ApJL
          We discuss the possibility of detecting the presence of
          primordial black holes (PBHs), such as those that might account
          for galactic dark matter, using modification of pulsar timing
          residuals when PBHs pass within ~1000 AU and impart impulse
          accelerations to the Earth. With this technique, PBHs with
          masses around 10^{25} g (~0.1 lunar mass) can be detected.
          Currently, the constraints on the abundance of such dark matter
          candidates are weak. A 30 year-long monitoring campaign with
          the proposed Square Kilometer Array (SKA) can rule out a PBH
          fraction more than ~1/10 in the solar neighborhood in the form
          of dark matter with mass ~10^{25} g.


   
