          VLM binaries from the literature, have properties that differ
          significantly from older field VLM binaries in that the young
          systems have wider separations and lower mass ratios,
          supporting the idea that VLM binaries undergo significant
          dynamical evolution ~5 - 10 Myr after their formation. The
          range of separations of these binaries, four of which are over
          30 AU, argues against the ejection scenario of brown dwarf
          formation. While several of the young, VLM binaries discovered
          in this study have lower binding energies than the previously
          suggested minimum for VLM binaries, the apparent minimum is
          still significantly higher than that found among higher mass
          binaries. We suggest that this discrepancy may be due to the
          small mass of a VLM binary relative to the average perturbing
          star, leading to more substantial changes in their binding
          energy over time.


   
